Missing Values HeatMap splited into 8 groups for readability¶

In [45]:
# Number of groups
num_groups = 8

# Split column names into 4 groups
col_groups = np.array_split(df.columns, num_groups)

# Loop through groups and plot each
for i, cols in enumerate(col_groups, 1):
    plt.figure(figsize=(22, 10))
    sns.heatmap(df[cols].isnull(), yticklabels=False, cbar=False, cmap='viridis')
    plt.title(f"Missing Values Heatmap - Group {i}", fontsize=22, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
    plt.show()

Calculate missing percentages¶

In [47]:
missing_percentage = df.isnull().sum() / len(df) * 100

# Split into 4 groups
col_groups = np.array_split(missing_percentage.index, num_groups)

# Loop through groups and plot each
for i, cols in enumerate(col_groups, 1):
    plt.figure(figsize=(22, 6))
    missing_percentage[cols].plot(kind='bar')
    plt.xlabel('Columns')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage')
    plt.title(f'Percentage of Missing Values - Group {i}', fontsize=25, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
    plt.show()

Handling inconsistent formatting¶

(1) Replaces spaces " " with underscores "_"¶

(2) Removes any characters not in A–Z, a–z, 0–9, or _ (underscore).¶

In [53]:
# Strip spaces and replace long text with shorter labels
df.columns = (
    df.columns
    .str.strip()
    .str.replace(" ", "_")
    .str.replace(r"[^A-Za-z0-9_]", "", regex=True)
)

print(df.columns[:20])  # preview cleaned names

regex expressions:¶

(1) \s{2,} → two or more spaces in a row.¶

(2) ^\s → space(s) at the beginning of the string.¶

(3) \s$ → space(s) at the end of the string.¶

Extra-Insight 2 – Education vs. Gender Gap¶

fill_value=0¶

*At education level may not have both genders in the dataset, so instead of NaN it writes **0,00***¶

In [177]:
# Calculate distribution of Male/Female within each education level
edu_gender = (
    df_map[df_map['gender_mapped'].isin(['M','F'])]
    .groupby('edu_mapped')['gender_mapped']
    .value_counts(normalize=True)   # gives proportions (0 to 1)
    .unstack(fill_value=0)          # reshape: columns = ['F','M'], rows = edu levels
    * 100                           # convert to percentages
)

# Plot unstacked bar chart
edu_gender.plot(kind='bar', stacked=False)
plt.title('Gender % by Education', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
plt.xlabel('Edu Level', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Respondents', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.legend(title="Gender", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1))  # move legend to right
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Education vs. Gender Gap (same plot,different way)¶

In [179]:
edu_gender = (
    df_map[df_map['gender_mapped'].isin(['M','F'])]
    .groupby('edu_mapped')['gender_mapped']
    .value_counts(normalize=True)
    .unstack()
    .assign(Female_pct=lambda x: x['F']*100)
    .assign(Male_pct=lambda x: x['M']*100)   
)
# Plot stacked bar chart
edu_gender[['Female_pct','Male_pct']].plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)
plt.legend(title="Gender", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1))  # move legend to right
plt.title('Gender % by Education', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
plt.xlabel('Edu Level', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Respondents', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# ----------------------------
# Compute Top 5 Insights
# ----------------------------

insights = {
    # 1. Gender balance (Female %)
    "Female respondents (%)": df_map['gender_mapped'].eq("F").mean() * 100,

    # 2. Most common continent (Top)
    "Top Continent: " + df_map['Continent'].mode()[0]: 
        df_map['Continent'].value_counts(normalize=True).iloc[0] * 100,

    # 3. Most common education level
    "Top Education: " + df_map['edu_mapped'].mode()[0]: 
        df_map['edu_mapped'].value_counts(normalize=True).iloc[0] * 100,

    # 4. Most common role
    "Top Role: " + df_map['role_mapped'].mode()[0]: 
        df_map['role_mapped'].value_counts(normalize=True).iloc[0] * 100,

    # 5. Non-coders who still want to learn
    "Non-coders want to learn (%)": (
        df_map[df_map['exp_mapped']=="Non_Coder"]["Q6"]
        .str.contains("want to learn", case=False, na=False)
        .mean() * 100
    )
}

# ----------------------------
# Plotting Dashboard
# ----------------------------
labels = list(insights.keys())
values = list(insights.values())

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(x=values, y=labels, palette="coolwarm")

plt.title("Top 5 Survey Insights", fontsize=17, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
plt.xlabel("Percentage (%)", fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel("")
plt.xlim(0, 100)

# Add value labels
for i, v in enumerate(values):
    plt.text(v + 1, i, f"{v:.1f}%", va='center', fontsize=10)

plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# ---- 1. pick only the top 5 insights to visualise --------------------------
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 2, figsize=(16, 12))
fig.suptitle('Top 5 Insights – Kaggle Survey 2021', fontsize=18, fontweight='bold')

# 1. Age distribution
sns.countplot(y='age_mapped', data=df_map,
              order=df_map['age_mapped'].value_counts().index,
              palette='Blues_r', ax=axes[0,0])
axes[0,0].set_title('Insight 1 – Age Skewed to Early-Career', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
axes[0,0].set_xlabel('Respondents')

# 2. Gender split
gender_pct = df_map['gender_mapped'].value_counts(normalize=True) * 100
sns.barplot(x=gender_pct.index, y=gender_pct.values,
            palette='Set2', ax=axes[0,1])
axes[0,1].set_title('Insight 2 – 3:1 Male Majority', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
axes[0,1].set_ylabel('%')
for i, v in enumerate(gender_pct.values):
    axes[0,1].text(i, v+1, f'{v:.1f}%', ha='center')

# 3. Education level
sns.countplot(y='edu_mapped', data=df_map,
              order=df_map['edu_mapped'].value_counts().index,
              palette='Greens_r', ax=axes[1,0])
axes[1,0].set_title('Insight 3 – Master’s Most Common', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
axes[1,0].set_xlabel('Respondents')

# 4. Coding experience
sns.countplot(y='exp_mapped', data=df_map,
              order=df_map['exp_mapped'].value_counts().index,
              palette='Oranges_r', ax=axes[1,1])
axes[1,1].set_title('Insight 4 – Peak at 3-5 yrs (Intermediate)', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
axes[1,1].set_xlabel('Respondents')

# 5. Top-10 Countries vs Experience (stacked bar)
top10 = df_map['Q3'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index
ct = pd.crosstab(df_map['Q3'], df_map['exp_mapped']).loc[top10]
ct.plot(kind='barh', stacked=True, ax=axes[2,0], colormap='tab20')
axes[2,0].set_title('Insight 5 – Country vs Experience', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', style='italic')
axes[2,0].set_xlabel('Respondents')
axes[2,0].legend(title='Experience', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1))

# remove the empty subplot
fig.delaxes(axes[2,1])

plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.03, 1, 0.97])
plt.show()

age_df = (df_map['age_mapped']
          .value_counts()
          .rename_axis('Age_Bucket')
          .reset_index(name='Respondents'))

# 2) interactive bar
fig_age = px.bar(
    age_df,
    x='Age_Bucket',
    y='Respondents',
    text='Respondents',   # Display counts on bars
    title="Insight 1 – Age Skewed to Early-Career",
    color='Respondents',  # Color bars by count value
    color_continuous_scale='Blues'
)

    texttemplate='%{text:,}',  # Format numbers with commas
    textposition='outside',    # Place labels above bars
    hovertemplate='<b>%{x}</b><br>Respondents: %{y:,}'
)

fig_age.update_layout(

)

5) Interactive heatmap: Country vs Experience¶

In [920]:
top10 = df_map['Q3'].value_counts().nlargest(10).index
ct = pd.crosstab(df_map['Q3'], df_map['exp_mapped']).loc[top10]

# Calculate percentages for better interpretation
ct_percent = ct.div(ct.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100  # Row percentages

fig_heat = px.imshow(
    ct_percent.values,  # Use percentages instead of raw counts
    x=ct.columns, 
    y=ct.index,
    aspect='auto',
    color_continuous_scale='viridis',  # Professional color scheme
    title="<b>Insight 5 –</b> Experience Distribution by Country (Top 10)",
    labels=dict(x="Experience Level", y="Country", color="Percentage"),
    zmin=0,  # Ensure consistent scale
    zmax=40  # Adjust based on your data
)

# Professional formatting
fig_heat.update_traces(
    hovertemplate='<b>%{y}</b><br>Experience: %{x}<br>Percentage: %{z:.1f}%<extra></extra>',
    text=ct.values,  # Show raw counts on hover
    texttemplate='%{z:.0f}%'  # Show percentages on cells
)

# White background and clean layout
fig_heat.update_layout(
    plot_bgcolor='white',
    paper_bgcolor='white',
    font=dict(family="Arial", size=12, color="#333333"),
    title=dict(
        x=0.001,
        y=0.95,  # Move title down slightly
        font=dict(size=25, color="#2c3e50", family='Times New Roman')
    ),

    # Add top margin to create space between title and heatmap
    margin=dict(
        t=220,  # Increase top margin
        b=80,
        l=80,
        r=80
    ),
    
    xaxis=dict(
        title_font=dict(size=20, color="#30008C"),
        tickfont=dict(size=14, color="#64E000"),
        tickangle=45
    ),
    yaxis=dict(
        title_font=dict(size=20, color="#64E000"),
        tickfont=dict(size=14, color="#30008C")
    ),
    coloraxis_colorbar=dict(
        title="Percentage %",
        title_side="right",
        thickness=15,
        len=0.75,
        title_font=dict(size=26, color="#30008C", family='Times New Roman'),
        
    ),
    width=950,  # Adjust size
    height=700
)

# Position x-axis on top
fig_heat.update_xaxes(side='top')

# Add grid-like borders for better readability

    xgap=1,  # Horizontal gap between cells
    ygap=1,  # Vertical gap between cells
    showscale=True  # Ensure colorbar is visible
)

    xref="paper", yref="paper",

    showarrow=False,
    font=dict(size=10, color="gray"),
    align="center"
